  "body": "/kind feature\r\n\r\nIn 1.7 we added the capability to encrypt secrets at the database layer using keys provided in a file on disk on the master. The next logical step is to protect those keys using a Key Management Service such as Vault or the KMS's provided by the major cloud providers. \r\n\r\nIn 1.8 via [48574](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/48574) we added a plugin mechanism and an implementation for Google Cloud KMS.  But this is based on the existing cloud provider integration point, so doesn't help the in-flight [Vault implementation](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/51760) or any other non-cloud providers. See [design doc for more details](https://docs.google.com/document/d/19SbqLrSC_MpmxbLCxasubRJLaZxgqfw1KeIwg3fHHLU/edit).\r\n\r\nAs @luxas states in the PR:\r\n\r\n> For beta, this has to work with out of tree cloud providers, and API server <-> KMS integration should > be done via some kind of interface, but not by compiling the KMS code into the API server.\r\n\r\nThis bug will track the effort to add that API interface.\r\n\r\n@lavalamp \r\n\r\n@kubernetes/sig-api-machinery-feature-requests\r\n@kubernetes/sig-auth-misc",
